atrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Gaelic equivalent of <b>Adam</b> ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Adam         ap Cynhaethwy was born in 1158, in Grosmont, Monmouthshire, Wales, United Kingdom, his father, Cynan Osglog ap Aeddan, was 32 and his mother, Cynhaethwy Verch Aeddan, was 22. He had at least 3 sons with Hawisia de Somery."},"et":{"1158–":"1158–Surnud","1158–Male":"1158–Surnud","1162–Female":"1162–Surnud","1190–1230":"1190–1230","1190–Male":"1190–Surnud","1280–Male":"1280–Surnud","1127–Male":"1127–Surnud","1137–Female":"1137–Surnud","1190":"1190","about 1280":"umbes 1280","1127":"1127","1137":"1137","1158":"1158","1230":"1230","1162":"1162","1280":"1280","Grosmont, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Grosmont, Monmouthshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Ergyng, Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1158–":"1158–Kuollut","1158–Male":"1158–Kuollut","1162–Female":"1162–Kuollut","1190–1230":"1190–1230","1190–Male":"1190–Kuollut","1280–Male":"1280–Kuollut","1127–Male":"1127–Kuollut","1137–Female":"1137–Kuollut","1190":"1190","about 1280":"noin 1280","1127":"1127","1137":"1137","1158":"1158","1230":"1230","1162":"1162","1280":"1280","Grosmont, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Grosmont, Monmouthshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Ergyng, Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, England","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1158–":"1158–Décédé","1158–Male":"1158–Décédé","1162–Female":"1162–Décédée","1190–1230":"1190–1230","1190–Male":"1190–Décédé","1280–Male":"1280–Décédé","1127–Male":"1127–Décédé","1137–Female":"1137–Décédée","1190":"1190","about 1280":"environ 1280","1127":"1127","1137":"1137","1158":"1158","1230":"1230","1162":"1162","1280":"1280","Grosmont, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Grosmont, Monmouthshire, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni","Ergyng, Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, Angleterre","England":"Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummar